Title: Observation
Notes: GNR LOC OF MARSH ROOST  Six cranes flew southeast out of the marsh and 28 others were seen northwest of the marsh in soybean stubble. Based on prior years experience and the different directions, I do believe these were separate cranes. I rechecked on November 1 and saw a similar pattern where 15 flew southeast and 26 were found out in fields 3 miles west northwest. This year the closest corn is not yet harvested so numbers are lower than in some prior years. Once corn is harvested, the closer locations are more attractive.

The Cranes could not be visually observed in the tall grass/cattails of the marsh.  So I don't know if that is a ground count or a point count. Title: Observation
Notes: Twenty five cranes entered the back of marsh between 5:15 and 5:19. This year, the water was shallow with some muddy portions visible.  I did not notice any cranes rise out of the marsh or fly back and forth to resettle themselves, but it was very quiet, unlike cranes who remain. The only consistent sounds I heard were wood ducks calling repeatedly, also unusual.  Did not see any hunters or hear gunshots.  However, watched 7 flyovers at 5:00 pm and 33 flyovers after 5:20.  All were headed due NW from marsh, some coming from further south, possibly from another roost off Sharon Hollow Rd.  I briefly checked that same spot earlier near 4 PM and heard two cranes call, but did not see them.  That area had numerous waterfowl, but no standing cranes out in open where they have stood in past years.  The water may have been deeper this year. Temp: 53 degrees dropping to 49 degrees by 5:50 pm when I left; partially cloudy; calm at 4:11PM but windy after 5:30PM.

Title: Observation 6943
Notes:
Locke Township, Ingham County, Michigan--74 cranes were observed flying over in small groups, mainly from the southwest over the trees, but they all continued flying north/northeast. No cranes (0) landed or stayed to roost at this location this year. They may have flown to the Scenic Lake area (Leisure Lake) where Sandhills have been counted in past years, but that's just a guess.

We had seen cranes in this area in previous months, but they don't seem to visit the pond much anymore. The pond is getting rather shallow and muddy. Also, the surrounding fields were planted to soybeans rather than corn this year which they don't care to eat.

Title: Observation 6944
Notes:
Rush Township, Shiawassee County, Michigan--Parmenter Marsh roost [at Al-Par Peat Company, c/o Brian Parmenter, 5900 Henderson Road, Elsie, MI 48831, PH: (989) 661-7850].

While this count is substantially higher than my counts from a couple of years ago, I believe that it is probably still an undercount. I could not view the southerly approach. Also the cranes came is so fast and heavily that it was a challenge to count them accurately, even with image-stabilized binoculars and a partner to write the numbers down. Perhaps I will have to arrange for assistants in the future!

Observation was made during flyover from the corner of W Allan Rd and N Friegel Rd (Latitude: 43.100443359090264 Longitude: -84.26539106634051). There were hundreds of cranes on the ground in the cut corn fields to the southeast, in the north half of section 17. Sandhill Cranes also flew in high from the north, northeast, and east, and as they came in, all the cranes on the ground lifted off to join them, and all funneled west into Parmenter Marsh which is primarily in Section 18. These played-out peat bogs have been terraformed by the owner into a waterfowl wetlands which has no springs and is fed by agricultural run-off only. The eastern side of Section 18 is still under construction and is mostly bare earth with some water but little vegetation. The cranes prefer the western portion of the section where the water is deeper and hidden by cattails, etc.

Title: Observation 6981
Notes: Crane behavior during this census made a normally guesstimate count into a very wild guess.  1)  The majority of cranes left this roost Thursday, 21 October.  That count the previous day was approximately 800 birds.  2)  The birds did not use only one roost as traditionally they have.  This year two roosts separated by 2 miles were used.  3)  The cranes this year did not leave the foraging fields at near sunset and fly to the roost as has been traditional practice.  Instead, they stayed in the fields long after sunset. It was then so dark, I would only hear them fly to the roost.

Title: Observation 7337
Notes: Pond at the SW corner of intersection of S Corey and W Colby Rds, Locke Township, Ingham County, MI. No cranes at all viewed on this date at this pond which is mostly damp mud and turning to meadow. This year it was surrounded by harvested soybean fields which the cranes do not prefer. Corn harvesting was busy everywhere in the wider area. Also barking dogs and rifle shots were heard to the north. On previous visits: 10/23/22 two cranes at pond and six more in township; 10/11/22 no cranes at mid-afternoon; 10/04/22 six cranes at pond and three more in township; 10/01/22 twelve cranes at the pond and three more in township. Crane numbers at this site are dwindling.

Title: Observation 7380
Notes: Upon arrival at 4:55PM, 320 cranes, counted with clicker, were mostly sitting in a grassy field to the east of the pond, with a few standing in the water of the shallow pond at the north end of the pond.  Just before it became too dark to see, 196 cranes were observed roosting at southern end of the pond.  The other birds had flown out, most to the south towards the Sharon Hollow marshes.  I do not know whether I should list the 320 counted at 4:55PM or the 196 seen at 7:06PM.  Also observed: 11 cranes, 6 Wilson's snipe, 2 killdeer, 2 pectoral sandpipers, 1 great blue heron, 1 great egret, 1 mallard, 50 red-winged blackbirds, 1 rusty blackbird, 2 crows,, 3 mourning doves, 5 eastern bluebirds, 1 downy woodpecker, 1 hairy woodpecker, 1 pileated woodpecker, 1 dark-eyed junco, and 1 American robin

Title: Observation 7420
Notes: This count takes place at the NIPSCO power plant.  Right before the active count time a coal train ran between me and the crane pond & blocked my view.  I suspect many cranes left the pond then and flew to the north where I can't see them.  The 347 cranes I counted were all higher in the sky & moving mostly from the SE toward the power plant fields.  Normally in other years they have lifted off the south pond and flown out to fields to the SW.  Also my last 98 cranes were within the 12 minutes after I should have stopped counting.  Since the sky was still active, I kept counting.  Within the official 60 minutes (30+30) around sunrise I only had 249 cranes.

Notes: Pond at the SW corner of intersection of S Corey and W Colby Rds, Locke Township, Ingham County, MI. No cranes at all viewed on this date at this pond which has been mostly damp mud and sometimes shallow water after a heavy rain. This year it was surrounded by unharvested corn fields. Corn harvesting was busy elsewhere in the wider area. On previous visits: 10/02/23 two cranes at pond, and eight plus fourteen more in flight within the township, but they did not roost at the pond; 09/23/23 two cranes at pond only. Crane numbers at this site are dwindling.
